  1. Why is the contour plot for multivariate normal density in Figure @ref(fig:contour-boundary)(b) tilted from southwest to northeast, but the contour plot in Figure @ref(fig:contour-boundary)(a) is not tilted?

Contour plots illustrating a multivariate normal density with (a) no correlation between error terms, and (b) positive correlation between error terms.

The difference in the tilt of the contour plots in Figures (a) and (b) is due to the correlation structure specified in the covariance matrix (\(\Sigma\)) for the multivariate normal distribution. This means that the the covariance terms are zero. In a diagonal covariance matrix, the variables are uncorrelated, and the contours of the multivariate normal distribution are aligned with the coordinate axes

  1. Give a short rule in your own words describing when an interpretation of an estimated coefficient should “hold constant” another covariate or “set to 0” that covariate (see Section @ref(interp:modeld)).

When interpreting an estimated coefficient, you should hold constant another covariate when you want to isolate the effect of the variable of interest while keeping the other covariate constant at a specific value. On the other hand, you should set to 0 a covariate when it is a categorical variable, and you want to compare the group represented by 0 to the reference group, understanding the change in the dependent variable when that specific covariate is absent.

generate_scatter_plot <- function(data, x_var, y_var, x_label, y_label) {
  ggplot(data = data, aes(x = !!rlang::sym(x_var), y = !!rlang::sym(y_var))) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "lm", color = "red") +
    ylab(y_label) +
    xlab(x_label)
}

d. Write out Model C, using both separate Level One and Level Two models as well as a composite model. Be sure to express distributions for error terms. How many parameters must be estimated in Model C?

Level 1: \[a_i + b_i \cdot \text{instructor}_{ij} + c_i \cdot \text{students}_{ij}\]

Level 2: \[\alpha_0 + \alpha_1 \cdot \text{compqb}_i + u_i \] \[\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{compqb}_i + v_i \] \[\gamma_0 + \gamma_1 \cdot \text{compqb}_i + w_i \]

Composite: \[\alpha_0 + \alpha_1 \cdot \text{compqbi} + \beta_0 \cdot \text{instructor}_{ij} + \beta_1 \cdot \text{compqbi} \cdot \text{instructor}_{ij} + \] \[ \gamma_0 \cdot \text{students}_{ij} + \gamma_1 \cdot \text{compqbi} \cdot \text{students}_{ij} + [u_i + v_i \cdot \text{instructor}_{ij} + w_i \cdot \text{students}_{ij}] \]

variance-covariance structure: \[ \begin{bmatrix} \sigma^2_u & 0 & 0 \\ \sigma_{uv} & \sigma^2_v & 0 \\ \sigma_{uw} & \sigma_{vw} & \sigma^2_w \end{bmatrix} \]

Airbnb in Chicago. @Trinh2018 collected data on 1561 Airbnb listings in Chicago from August 2016, and then they merged in information from the neighborhood (out of 43 in Chicago) where the listing was located. We can examine traits that are associated with listings that command a higher price. Conduct an EDA, build a multilevel model, and interpret model coefficients to answer questions such as: What are characteristics of a higher priced listing? Are the most influential traits associated with individual listings or entire neighborhoods? Are there intriguing interactions where the effect of one variable depends on levels of another?

    The following variables can be found in airbnb.csv or derived from the variables found there:

    • overall_satisfaction = rating on a 0-5 scale.
    • satisfaction = 1 if overall_satisfaction is 5, 0 otherwise
    • price = price for one night (in dollars)
    • reviews = number of reviews posted
    • room_type = Entire home/apt, Private room, or Shared room
    • accommodates = number of people the unit can hold
    • bedrooms = number of bedrooms
    • minstay = minimum length of stay (in days)
    • neighborhood = neighborhood where unit is located (1 of 43)
    • district = district where unit is located (1 of 9)
    • WalkScore = quality of the neighborhood for walking (0-100)
    • TransitScore = quality of the neighborhood for public transit (0-100)
    • BikeScore = quality of the neighborhood for biking (0-100)
    • PctBlack = proportion of black residents in a neighborhood
    • HighBlack = 1 if PctBlack above .60, 0 otherwise
